      <!-- What is an SBA Loan -->
      <div class="prose max-w-none mb-12">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-heading font-bold text-steel-blue mb-4">What is an SBA Loan?</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-charcoal leading-relaxed mb-4">
          The SBA (Small Business Administration) doesn't actually lend you money directly. Instead, they partner with banks and lenders to <strong>guarantee</strong> a portion of your loan—typically up to 85%. This guarantee reduces the risk for lenders, making them more willing to approve loans for small businesses that might not otherwise qualify.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-steel-blue p-6 rounded-lg my-6">
          <h3 class="font-heading font-semibold text-steel-blue mb-2">Quick Definition</h3>
          <p class="text-charcoal mb-0">
            <strong>SBA Guarantee:</strong> The SBA promises to repay the lender a percentage of your loan if you default. This makes banks more comfortable lending to startups and small businesses.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-lg text-charcoal leading-relaxed mb-4">
          There are several types of SBA loans, but the most common are:
        </p>

        <ul class="list-disc pl-8 space-y-3 text-lg text-charcoal mb-6">
          <li><strong>SBA 7(a) Loan:</strong> The most popular. Up to $5 million for working capital, equipment, real estate, or refinancing debt.</li>
          <li><strong>SBA 504 Loan:</strong> Specifically for purchasing fixed assets like buildings or heavy equipment. Up to $5.5 million.</li>
          <li><strong>SBA Microloan:</strong> Smaller loans up to $50,000 for startups and small businesses.</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="text-lg text-charcoal leading-relaxed">
          For most small business owners and startups, the <strong>7(a) loan</strong> is what you'll be applying for, so that's what we'll focus on.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- The Complete Requirements Checklist -->
