        <h2 class="text-3xl font-heading font-bold text-steel-blue mb-6">The Complete SBA Loan Requirements Checklist</h2>

        <p class="text-lg text-charcoal leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Here's everything you'll need. I've organized this based on what banks actually ask for, not just what the SBA website says. Trust me—there's a difference.
        </p>

        <!-- Section 1: Business Documents -->
        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-steel-blue mb-4">1. Business Formation Documents</h3>

          <ul class="space-y-3 text-lg text-charcoal">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Business License:</strong> Proof your business is legally registered in your state.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Articles of Incorporation or LLC Operating Agreement:</strong> Shows your business structure.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Business Lease or Deed:</strong> If you rent or own your business location.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Franchise Agreement:</strong> Only if you're operating a franchise.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <div class="bg-yellow-50 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 p-4 mt-4">
            <p class="text-sm text-charcoal mb-0">
              <strong>Pro Tip:</strong> If you're a new business without all these documents yet, don't panic. Some lenders work with startups, but you'll need an even stronger business plan to compensate.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 2: Financial Documents -->
        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-steel-blue mb-4">2. Financial Documents (The Big One)</h3>

          <p class="text-charcoal mb-4">
            This is where most people get stuck. Banks want to see that you understand your numbers and can realistically pay back the loan.
          </p>

          <ul class="space-y-3 text-lg text-charcoal">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Business Tax Returns (Last 3 Years):</strong> If you're an existing business. Startups won't have these yet.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Personal Tax Returns (Last 3 Years):</strong> Yes, your personal taxes matter. Banks want to see you're financially responsible.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Personal Financial Statement:</strong> A list of all your assets (house, car, savings) and liabilities (debts, loans).</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Bank Statements (Last 3-6 Months):</strong> Both business and personal accounts.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Balance Sheet:</strong> A snapshot of what your business owns and owes.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Profit & Loss Statement (P&L):</strong> Shows your revenue and expenses over time.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-steel-blue p-4 mt-4">
            <h4 class="font-heading font-semibold text-steel-blue mb-2">Quick Definitions</h4>
            <ul class="text-sm text-charcoal space-y-2 mb-0">
              <li><strong>Balance Sheet:</strong> Think of it like a financial selfie. It shows what you own (assets), what you owe (liabilities), and what's left over (equity) at a specific point in time.</li>
              <li><strong>P&L Statement:</strong> Like a movie of your finances. It shows income and expenses over a period (usually monthly or annually) to determine if you're profitable.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 3: Business Plan -->
        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-steel-blue mb-4">3. Comprehensive Business Plan</h3>

          <p class="text-charcoal mb-4">
            This is the most important document. Your business plan tells the story of your business and proves you can repay the loan.
          </p>

          <p class="text-charcoal mb-4 font-semibold">
            Your business plan must include:
          </p>

          <ul class="space-y-3 text-lg text-charcoal">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Executive Summary:</strong> A 1-2 page overview of your business, what you do, and why you need the loan.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Company Description:</strong> What problem you solve, who your customers are, and what makes you different.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Market Analysis:</strong> Who are your competitors? How big is your market? What's your target customer profile?</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Organization & Management:</strong> Who's running the company? What's their experience?</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Products or Services:</strong> Exactly what you're selling and how you make money.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Marketing & Sales Strategy:</strong> How will you find and keep customers?</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Financial Projections (24-36 months):</strong> This is critical. You need month-by-month projections showing revenue, expenses, cash flow, and profitability.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
              <span><strong>Funding Request:</strong> How much you need, what you'll use it for, and how you'll pay it back.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 mt-4">
            <p class="text-sm text-charcoal mb-0">
              <strong>Reality Check:</strong> Most business plan templates online are too generic. Banks can tell when you've just filled in a template. Your plan needs to show you've done real research and understand your numbers.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Section 4: Additional Documents -->
        <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-heading font-bold text-steel-blue mb-4">4. Additional Documents</h3>

          <ul class="space-y-3 text-lg text-charcoal">
            <li class="flex items-start">
              <span class="text-tech-teal mr-3 mt-1">✓</span>
